    <h1>4 THE SCARE-ATHON</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20200920/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-09-20"><time>2020-09-20</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE | FEATURES</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>Some peo­ple need to feel fear to feel alive. When the gory slaugh­ter­house-in-space drama Event Hori­zon (1997) was re­leased, it flopped. But over the years, it has found a cult fol­low­ing.</p>
    <p>When Stan­ley Kubrick’s 1980 adap­ta­tion of Stephen King’s 1977 novel The Shin­ing was re­leased, the writer hated it – and still does, ap­par­ently.</p>
    <p>The vi­o­lent Hos­tel (2005) will have you ei­ther nau­se­ated or grin­ning from ear to ear, but it is worth a watch if only to see the con­tro­versy it un­leashed with its de­pic­tion of Eastern Europe as a flesh-man­gling trap for in­no­cent Amer­i­can trav­ellers.</p>
    <p>The Ring (2002), the Amer­i­can re­make of the 1998 Ja­panese hit, was so suc­cess­ful, it sent Western ex­ec­u­tives scour­ing Asian hor­ror vaults for more op­por­tu­ni­ties.</p>
    <p>Watch on Net­flix:</p>
    <p>The Shin­ing (1980) Event Hori­zon (1997) The Ring (2002) Hos­tel (2005)</p>

